### Architectural & Code Quality Analysis

🟠 **HIGH** `packages/forgescript/src/core/Experiment.ts:170` – Potential CSS Injection via Direct DOM Manipulation
Directly setting `document.body.style` properties from experiment options without sanitization creates a security risk. If an experiment configuration is loaded from an external source, a malicious value for `backgroundColor` or `cursor` could be used to inject arbitrary CSS, potentially enabling UI redressing or other phishing-style attacks.

```typescript
// context_start_text
    // Set background color
    if (this.options.backgroundColor) {
      document.body.style.backgroundColor = this.options.backgroundColor;
    }

    // Set cursor
    if (this.options.cursor) {
      document.body.style.cursor = this.options.cursor;
    }
// context_end_text
```

→ **Fix**: Avoid direct manipulation of the `document.body`. Instead, apply styles to a dedicated container element for the experiment. Sanitize any values that are used to set style properties. For colors, validate them against a regex for valid color formats (hex, rgb, etc.). For cursors, validate against an allow-list of valid CSS cursor values.

```typescript
// Example of a simple color sanitizer
function sanitizeColor(color: string): string | null {
  // Basic regex for hex, rgb, rgba, hsl, hsla, and named colors
  const colorRegex = /^(#([0-9a-f]{3}){1,2}|(rgb|rgba|hsl|hsla)\(.*\)|[a-z]+)$/i;
  if (colorRegex.test(color)) {
    return color;
  }
  console.warn(`Invalid color value detected: ${color}`);
  return null; // Or a default color
}

// In Experiment.ts, inside initializeEnvironment
const safeColor = this.options.backgroundColor ? sanitizeColor(this.options.backgroundColor) : null;
if (safeColor) {
  // Apply to a container element, not document.body
  experimentContainer.style.backgroundColor = safeColor;
}
```

🟠 **HIGH** `packages/devices/src/AudioDevice.ts:78` – Event Listener Memory Leak
The `cleanup` method in `AudioDevice` creates a new function instance with `.bind(this)`, which does not match the instance created in `initialize`. As a result, the `devicechange` event listener is never removed, leading to a memory leak. This is particularly problematic in a long-running application or a test environment where many `AudioDevice` instances might be created and destroyed.

```typescript
// context_start_text
    navigator.mediaDevices?.removeEventListener(
      'devicechange',
      this.handleDeviceChange.bind(this),
    );
// context_end_text
```

→ **Fix**: Store the bound event handler in an instance property during initialization and use that stored reference for both `addEventListener` and `removeEventListener`.

```typescript
// In AudioDevice class
export class AudioDevice extends Device {
  // ...
  private isRecording: boolean = false;
  private boundDeviceChangeHandler = this.handleDeviceChange.bind(this); // Create bound handler once

  // ... in initialize()
  // Monitor device changes
  navigator.mediaDevices?.addEventListener(
    'devicechange',
    this.boundDeviceChangeHandler,
  );

  // ... in cleanup()
  navigator.mediaDevices?.removeEventListener(
    'devicechange',
    this.boundDeviceChangeHandler,
  );
  // ...
}
```

🟡 **MEDIUM** `packages/forgescript/src/index.ts:1` – Confusing and Overlapping APIs
The `forgescript` package exposes multiple, overlapping APIs for creating experiments: `ComponentForge`, `ForgeBuilder`, and a static `ForgeScript` object. This creates a confusing developer experience, increases the maintenance burden, and violates the "one clear way to do it" principle. The presence of `backward-compatibility.ts` further highlights this architectural friction.

→ **Fix**: Decide on a single, canonical API for experiment creation (the component-based approach with `ComponentForge` or `ForgeBuilder` seems most powerful and modern). Mark the other APIs as deprecated and provide a clear migration path in the documentation. The `ForgeScript` static object should be phased out in favor of the builder pattern.

🟡 **MEDIUM** `packages/forgescript/src/core/Experiment.ts:241` – Implicit Browser Fingerprinting
The `Experiment` class collects detailed browser and system information (`userAgent`, `screenResolution`, `viewportSize`) without an explicit mechanism for participant consent. This data can be used for browser fingerprinting, which has significant privacy implications and may be subject to regulations like GDPR.

```typescript
// context_start_text
          userAgent: navigator.userAgent,
          screenResolution: `${screen.width}x${screen.height}`,
          viewportSize: `${window.innerWidth}x${window.innerHeight}`,
        },
// context_end_text
```

→ **Fix**: Make data collection explicit and configurable. Add an option to the experiment configuration (e.g., `collectSystemInfo: boolean | 'full' | 'minimal'`) that is disabled by default. The documentation must clearly state what information is collected so researchers can obtain proper informed consent from participants.

🟡 **MEDIUM** `packages/forgescript/src/components/animation/AnimationComponent.ts:233` – In-place Array Modification Creates Side Effects
The `applyKeyframes` method sorts the `this.options.keyframes` array in-place. If the same `AnimationOptions` object is reused for multiple components, this will permanently alter the original object, which can lead to unexpected behavior and subtle bugs that are hard to trace.

```typescript
// context_start_text
    // Find surrounding keyframes
    const keyframes = this.options.keyframes.sort((a, b) => a.time - b.time);
    let startKeyframe = keyframes[0];
// context_end_text
```

→ **Fix**: Create a shallow copy of the `keyframes` array before sorting it to avoid modifying the original options object.

```typescript
// In AnimationComponent.ts, inside applyKeyframes()
const keyframes = [...this.options.keyframes].sort((a, b) => a.time - b.time);
```

🟢 **LOW** `packages/forgescript/src/index.ts:44` – Missing Type Imports
The file uses types like `ExperimentOptions`, `Experiment`, and `Timeline` without importing them. While this may work within the monorepo's TypeScript build process, it is poor practice. It makes the code harder to understand, less portable, and reliant on implicit compiler behavior.

```typescript
// context_start_text
  // Factory functions for common patterns
  createExperiment: (title: string, options?: ExperimentOptions) => {
    return new Experiment(crypto.randomUUID(), options).title(title);
  },
// context_end_text
```

→ **Fix**: Add explicit `import type` statements at the top of the file for all types used from other modules. This improves clarity and code robustness.

```typescript
import type { ExperimentOptions } from './core/Experiment.js';
import { Experiment } from './core/Experiment.js';
import { Timeline } from './core/Timeline.js';
// ... other imports
```

